# Spotify Web API (required for playlist import)
# Create an app at https://developer.spotify.com/dashboard
SPOTIFY_CLIENT_ID=
SPOTIFY_CLIENT_SECRET=

# Local dev: run `npm run server` in a second terminal, then `npm start`.
# The dev server reads this file via dotenv. CRA proxies /api → http://localhost:3001.

# --- Public / production (read this if you see 404 on “Load from Spotify”) ---
#
# The browser calls an HTTP API (see api/spotify-playlist.js). Uploading only the
# `build/` folder to GitHub Pages, S3, etc. will NOT include that API → 404.
#
# Option A — Netlify (same origin as the site, no REACT_APP URL needed):
#   1. Commit netlify.toml + netlify/functions/ + lib/ + api/ (or whole repo).
#   2. Site settings → Environment variables → add SPOTIFY_CLIENT_ID, SPOTIFY_CLIENT_SECRET.
#   3. Trigger a new deploy. The redirect serves POST /api/spotify-playlist → the function.
#
# Option B — Vercel (same origin, no extra env for the URL):
#   1. Push the whole repo (including /api and /lib).
#   2. Import the project on vercel.com; Framework Preset: Create React App.
#   3. In Vercel → Settings → Environment Variables, add:
#        SPOTIFY_CLIENT_ID, SPOTIFY_CLIENT_SECRET
#      (same values as in the Spotify Developer Dashboard.)
#   4. Deploy. The app can keep the default path /api/spotify-playlist.
#
# Option C — API on a different host than the static site:
#   Set this before `npm run build` so the browser calls the correct URL:
# REACT_APP_SPOTIFY_IMPORT_URL=https://your-api-host.example.com/api/spotify-playlist
#
# CORS: if the API is on another domain, set ALLOWED_ORIGIN on the API to your
# site origin (e.g. https://your-app.pages.dev) or use * for development only.

# Optional — restrict CORS on the Express dev server (comma-separated origins)
# ALLOWED_ORIGIN=http://localhost:3000,http://127.0.0.1:3000

# Optional — if the import API runs elsewhere during dev (default http://localhost:3001)
# SPOTIFY_PROXY_TARGET=http://localhost:3001
